06073nam a22008175i 9780748637706DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222010stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486377067 a10.1515/97807486377062doi  a(DE-B1597)616649  a(OCoLC)1306540933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aPR6037.P29bZ65 2010eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823.9142221 aGardiner, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Edinburgh Companion to Muriel Spark /cMichael Gardiner, Willy Maley. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEdinburgh Companions to Scottish Literature : ECSL00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editors’ Preface -- tBrief Biography of Muriel Spark -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE Muriel Spark and the Problems of Biography -- tCHAPTER TWO Poetic Perception in the Fiction of Muriel Spark -- tCHAPTER THREE Body and State in Spark’s Early Fiction -- tCHAPTER FOUR The Stranger Spark -- tCHAPTER FIVE Muriel Spark and the Politics of the Contemporary -- tCHAPTER SIX Spark, Modernism and Postmodernism -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Muriel Spark as Catholic Novelist -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Muriel Spark’s Break with Romanticism -- tCHAPTER NINE The Postwar Contexts of Spark’s Writing -- tCHAPTER TEN Muriel Spark’s Crimes of Wit -- tEndnotes -- tFurther Reading -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis Companion brings together an international 'Brodie set' of critics to trace the history, impact, reception and major themes of Spark's work, from her early poetry to her last novel. It encompasses the range of Spark's output, pursuing contextual lines of approach including biography, geography, gender, identity, nation and religion, and considering her legacy and continuing influence in the twenty-first century. Spark emerges here as a serious thinker on issues as diverse as the Welfare State, secularisation, decolonisation, and anti-psychiatry, and a writer whose work may be placed alongside Proust, Joyce, Nabokov, and Lessing.The critics collected here are mindful of how, although overwhelmingly known as a novelist, by the time of her first novel, The Comforters, in 1957, Spark already had a significant profile through poetry, biographical criticism, and literary journalism, as chair of the Poetry Society and editor of the Poetry Review, and as author or co-author of a number of scholarly studies of writers including Wordsworth, Mary Shelley, the Bröntes, Cardinal Newman, and John Masefield. Within a relatively modest space this Companion touches on the whole range of Spark's work and, in introducing the oeuvre thematically for those looking to explore this elegant and challenging author further, also sets the agenda for future Spark studies.Key FeaturesA collection of original, specially commissioned chapters by leading experts in the fieldCovers the whole spectrum of Spark's workAddresses the key issues and themes in Spark's work without losing sight of the questions of form and contentProvides original insights into the contexts of Spark's work as viewed through literary theory  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aCarruthers, Gerard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolocotroni, Vassiliki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Paddy, econtributor.